As a patient-focused organization, the University of Utah Health Sciences exists to enhance the health and well-being of people through patient care, research and education. Success in this mission requires a culture of collaboration, excellence, leadership, and respect. The Health Sciences Center seeks faculty and staff who are committed to the values of compassion, collaboration, innovation, responsibility, diversity, integrity, quality and trust that are integral to our mission.
Responsibilities
1. Provide evidence-based care to women including ordering and evaluation of diagnostic tests and management of minor complications.
2. Provide inpatient (CNM) and outpatient obstetrical care for essentially healthy women.
3. Provide individualized client teaching, counseling and anticipatory guidance for the current identified problem, weeks’ gestation, and social/cultural situation.
4. Perform accurate comprehensive health history, review of systems and physical examination, concluding with diagnosis and treatment.
5. Perform a comprehensive physical examination to identify the normal and abnormal changes associated with health and disease states.
6. Order, perform, and interpret diagnostic procedures and tests, as indicated by the history and physical examination, for pregnancy, acute and common primary care conditions.
7. Develop differential diagnoses based on clinical and laboratory data.
8. Differentiate and manage common primary care problems and other deviations from normal. Recognize emergencies and initiate emergency care/triage.
9. Manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. Initiate health promotion and disease prevention strategies that consider the individual’s age, developmental status, disability, culture, ethnicity, and sexual orientation to address their physical, psychosocial, and cultural needs.
10. Participate in the care of women with medical complications in collaboration with Obstetricians-Gynecologists and /or other physicians and health professionals as indicated and by sharing and receiving referrals for care with other professionals.
11. Complete necessary documentation appropriately, including coding and billing.
12. Instruct, supervise/precept and serve as mentor to students and trainees in medicine and nursing as assigned. Ensure a positive learning environment.
13. Contribute to site-specific quality improvement and data collection efforts.
14. Perform other duties as assigned.

About Sitka
At Sitka, we believe that EVERYONE deserves access to specialized healthcare. Founded in late 2018 by our Founder/CEO Kelsey Mellard, our mission is to foster informed, effective, and trusted care delivery for all patients by every provider. Timely access to specialty care is often out of reach for too many Americans, often because of the inefficiencies of the delivery system. Sitka is reimagining specialty care by giving primary care providers (PCPs) access to our network of specialist physicians. Our platform enables virtual consults for patient diagnosis and care between PCPs and specialists. With the help of Sitka and the specialists at Sitka Medical Associates, patients avoid unnecessary specialist visits and receive answers in hours, not weeks, all while keeping PCPs at the helm.

The University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center Department of Obstetrics and Gynecology is seeking a Board Certified/Board Active Candidate physician to join its Division of Gynecology. An OB-GYN, or Obstetrician-Gynecologist, diagnoses and treats various medical conditions that impact women’s health. The duties include diagnosing and monitoring illnesses and diseases, providing medical support to pregnant women, and performing routine check-ups on female patients.
ESSENTIAL DUTIES/RESPONSIBILITIES:
Diagnoses and treats conditions that affect women, such as certain types of cancer and conditions like menopause.
Works with expecting mothers to explain the childbirth process.
Performs routine checkups with patients.

The Women’s Health Nurse Practitioner (WHNP) hired into this position will manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. The position requires a considerable degree of independent skills and judgment necessary to monitor and respond to changes in patients’ condition.
As a patient-focused organization, the University of Utah Health Sciences exists to enhance the health and well-being of people through patient care, research and education. Success in this mission requires a culture of collaboration, excellence, leadership, and respect. The Health Sciences Center seeks faculty and staff who are committed to the values of compassion, collaboration, innovation, responsibility, diversity, integrity, quality and trust that are integral to our mission.
Responsibilities
1. Provide evidence-based care to women including ordering and evaluation of diagnostic tests and management of minor complications.
2. Provide outpatient obstetrical care for essentially healthy women.
3. Provide individualized client teaching, counseling and anticipatory guidance for the current identified problem, weeks’ gestation, and social/cultural situation.
4. Perform accurate comprehensive health history, review of systems and physical examination, concluding with diagnosis and treatment.
5. Perform a comprehensive physical examination to identify the normal and abnormal changes associated with health and disease states.
6. Order, perform, and interpret diagnostic procedures and tests, as indicated by the history and physical examination, for pregnancy, acute and common primary care conditions.
7. Develop differential diagnoses based on clinical and laboratory data.
8. Differentiate and manage common primary care problems and other deviations from normal. Recognize emergencies and initiate emergency care/triage.
9. Manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. Initiate health promotion and disease prevention strategies that consider the individual’s age, developmental status, disability, culture, ethnicity, and sexual orientation to address their physical, psychosocial, and cultural needs.
10. Participate in the care of women with medical complications in collaboration with Obstetricians-Gynecologists and /or other physicians and health professionals as indicated and by sharing and receiving referrals for care with other professionals.
11. Complete necessary documentation appropriately, including coding and billing.
12. Instruct, supervise/precept and serve as mentor to students and trainees in medicine and nursing as assigned. Ensure a positive learning environment.
13. Contribute to site-specific quality improvement and data collection efforts.
14. Perform other duties as assigned.

An OB-GYN, or Obstetrician-Gynecologist, diagnoses and treats various medical conditions that impact women’s health. The duties include diagnosing and monitoring illnesses and diseases, providing medical support to pregnant women, and performing routine check-ups on female patients.
ESSENTIAL DUTIES/RESPONSIBILITIES:
Diagnoses and treats conditions that affect women, such as certain types of cancer and conditions like menopause.
Works with expecting mothers to explain the childbirth process.
Performs routine checkups with patients.

The Women’s Health Nurse Practitioner (WHNP) hired into this position will manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. The position requires a considerable degree of independent skills and judgment necessary to monitor and respond to changes in patients’ condition.
As a patient-focused organization, the University of Utah Health Sciences exists to enhance the health and well-being of people through patient care, research and education. Success in this mission requires a culture of collaboration, excellence, leadership, and respect. The Health Sciences Center seeks faculty and staff who are committed to the values of compassion, collaboration, innovation, responsibility, diversity, integrity, quality and trust that are integral to our mission.
Responsibilities
1. Provide evidence-based care to women including ordering and evaluation of diagnostic tests and management of minor complications.
2. Provide outpatient obstetrical care for essentially healthy women.
3. Provide individualized client teaching, counseling and anticipatory guidance for the current identified problem, weeks’ gestation, and social/cultural situation.
4. Perform accurate comprehensive health history, review of systems and physical examination, concluding with diagnosis and treatment.
5. Perform a comprehensive physical examination to identify the normal and abnormal changes associated with health and disease states.
6. Order, perform, and interpret diagnostic procedures and tests, as indicated by the history and physical examination, for pregnancy, acute and common primary care conditions.
7. Develop differential diagnoses based on clinical and laboratory data.
8. Differentiate and manage common primary care problems and other deviations from normal. Recognize emergencies and initiate emergency care/triage.
9. Manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. Initiate health promotion and disease prevention strategies that consider the individual’s age, developmental status, disability, culture, ethnicity, and sexual orientation to address their physical, psychosocial, and cultural needs.
10. Participate in the care of women with medical complications in collaboration with Obstetricians-Gynecologists and /or other physicians and health professionals as indicated and by sharing and receiving referrals for care with other professionals.
11. Complete necessary documentation appropriately, including coding and billing.
12. Instruct, supervise/precept and serve as mentor to students and trainees in medicine and nursing as assigned. Ensure a positive learning environment.
13. Contribute to site-specific quality improvement and data collection efforts.
14. Perform other duties as assigned.

The Women’s Health Nurse Practitioner (WHNP) hired into this position will manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. The position requires a considerable degree of independent skills and judgment necessary to monitor and respond to changes in patients’ condition.
As a patient-focused organization, the University of Utah Health Sciences exists to enhance the health and well-being of people through patient care, research and education. Success in this mission requires a culture of collaboration, excellence, leadership, and respect. The Health Sciences Center seeks faculty and staff who are committed to the values of compassion, collaboration, innovation, responsibility, diversity, integrity, quality and trust that are integral to our mission.
Responsibilities
1. Provide evidence-based care to women including ordering and evaluation of diagnostic tests and management of minor complications.
2. Provide outpatient obstetrical care for essentially healthy women.
3. Provide individualized client teaching, counseling and anticipatory guidance for the current identified problem, weeks’ gestation, and social/cultural situation.
4. Perform accurate comprehensive health history, review of systems and physical examination, concluding with diagnosis and treatment.
5. Perform a comprehensive physical examination to identify the normal and abnormal changes associated with health and disease states.
6. Order, perform, and interpret diagnostic procedures and tests, as indicated by the history and physical examination, for pregnancy, acute and common primary care conditions.
7. Develop differential diagnoses based on clinical and laboratory data.
8. Differentiate and manage common primary care problems and other deviations from normal. Recognize emergencies and initiate emergency care/triage.
9. Manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. Initiate health promotion and disease prevention strategies that consider the individual’s age, developmental status, disability, culture, ethnicity, and sexual orientation to address their physical, psychosocial, and cultural needs.
10. Participate in the care of women with medical complications in collaboration with Obstetricians-Gynecologists and /or other physicians and health professionals as indicated and by sharing and receiving referrals for care with other professionals.
11. Complete necessary documentation appropriately, including coding and billing.
12. Instruct, supervise/precept and serve as mentor to students and trainees in medicine and nursing as assigned. Ensure a positive learning environment.
13. Contribute to site-specific quality improvement and data collection efforts.
14. Perform other duties as assigned.

As a patient-focused organization, the University of Utah Health Sciences exists to enhance the health and well-being of people through patient care, research and education. Success in this mission requires a culture of collaboration, excellence, leadership, and respect. The Health Sciences Center seeks faculty and staff who are committed to the values of compassion, collaboration, innovation, responsibility, diversity, integrity, quality and trust that are integral to our mission.
Responsibilities
1. Provide evidence-based care to women including ordering and evaluation of diagnostic tests and management of minor complications.
2. Provide outpatient obstetrical care for essentially healthy women.
3. Provide individualized client teaching, counseling and anticipatory guidance for the current identified problem, weeks’ gestation, and social/cultural situation.
4. Perform accurate comprehensive health history, review of systems and physical examination, concluding with diagnosis and treatment.
5. Perform a comprehensive physical examination to identify the normal and abnormal changes associated with health and disease states.
6. Order, perform, and interpret diagnostic procedures and tests, as indicated by the history and physical examination, for pregnancy, acute and common primary care conditions.
7. Develop differential diagnoses based on clinical and laboratory data.
8. Differentiate and manage common primary care problems and other deviations from normal. Recognize emergencies and initiate emergency care/triage.
9. Manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. Initiate health promotion and disease prevention strategies that consider the individual’s age, developmental status, disability, culture, ethnicity, and sexual orientation to address their physical, psychosocial, and cultural needs.
10. Participate in the care of women with medical complications in collaboration with Obstetricians-Gynecologists and /or other physicians and health professionals as indicated and by sharing and receiving referrals for care with other professionals.
11. Complete necessary documentation appropriately, including coding and billing.
12. Instruct, supervise/precept and serve as mentor to students and trainees in medicine and nursing as assigned. Ensure a positive learning environment.
13. Contribute to site-specific quality improvement and data collection efforts.
14. Perform other duties as assigned.

As a patient-focused organization, the University of Utah Health Sciences exists to enhance the health and well-being of people through patient care, research and education. Responsibilities
1. Provide evidence-based care to women including ordering and evaluation of diagnostic tests and management of minor complications.
2. Provide outpatient obstetrical care for essentially healthy women.
3. Provide individualized client teaching, counseling and anticipatory guidance for the current identified problem, weeks’ gestation, and social/cultural situation.
4. Perform accurate comprehensive health history, review of systems and physical examination, concluding with diagnosis and treatment.
5. Perform a comprehensive physical examination to identify the normal and abnormal changes associated with health and disease states.

9. Manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. Initiate health promotion and disease prevention strategies that consider the individual’s age, developmental status, disability, culture, ethnicity, and sexual orientation to address their physical, psychosocial, and cultural needs.
10. Participate in the care of women with medical complications in collaboration with Obstetricians-Gynecologists and /or other physicians and health professionals as indicated and by sharing and receiving referrals for care with other professionals.

13. Contribute to site-specific quality improvement and data collection efforts.
14. Perform other duties as assigned.

An OB-GYN, or Obstetrician-Gynecologist, diagnoses and treats various medical conditions that impact women’s health. The duties include diagnosing and monitoring illnesses and diseases, providing medical support to pregnant women, and performing routine check-ups on female patients.
ESSENTIAL DUTIES/RESPONSIBILITIES:
Diagnoses and treats conditions that affect women, such as certain types of cancer and conditions like menopause.
Works with expecting mothers to explain the childbirth process.
Performs routine checkups with patients.

The Women’s Health Nurse Practitioner (WHNP) hired into this position will manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. The position requires a considerable degree of independent skills and judgment necessary to monitor and respond to changes in patients’ condition.
As a patient-focused organization, the University of Utah Health Sciences exists to enhance the health and well-being of people through patient care, research and education. Success in this mission requires a culture of collaboration, excellence, leadership, and respect. The Health Sciences Center seeks faculty and staff who are committed to the values of compassion, collaboration, innovation, responsibility, diversity, integrity, quality and trust that are integral to our mission.
Responsibilities
1. Provide evidence-based care to women including ordering and evaluation of diagnostic tests and management of minor complications.
2. Provide outpatient obstetrical care for essentially healthy women.
3. Provide individualized client teaching, counseling and anticipatory guidance for the current identified problem, weeks’ gestation, and social/cultural situation.
4. Perform accurate comprehensive health history, review of systems and physical examination, concluding with diagnosis and treatment.
5. Perform a comprehensive physical examination to identify the normal and abnormal changes associated with health and disease states.
6. Order, perform, and interpret diagnostic procedures and tests, as indicated by the history and physical examination, for pregnancy, acute and common primary care conditions.
7. Develop differential diagnoses based on clinical and laboratory data.
8. Differentiate and manage common primary care problems and other deviations from normal. Recognize emergencies and initiate emergency care/triage.
9. Manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. Initiate health promotion and disease prevention strategies that consider the individual’s age, developmental status, disability, culture, ethnicity, and sexual orientation to address their physical, psychosocial, and cultural needs.
10. Participate in the care of women with medical complications in collaboration with Obstetricians-Gynecologists and /or other physicians and health professionals as indicated and by sharing and receiving referrals for care with other professionals.
11. Complete necessary documentation appropriately, including coding and billing.
12. Instruct, supervise/precept and serve as mentor to students and trainees in medicine and nursing as assigned. Ensure a positive learning environment.
13. Contribute to site-specific quality improvement and data collection efforts.
14. Perform other duties as assigned.

As a patient-focused organization, the University of Utah Health Sciences exists to enhance the health and well-being of people through patient care, research and education. Success in this mission requires a culture of collaboration, excellence, leadership, and respect. The Health Sciences Center seeks faculty and staff who are committed to the values of compassion, collaboration, innovation, responsibility, diversity, integrity, quality and trust that are integral to our mission.
Responsibilities
1. Provide evidence-based care to women including ordering and evaluation of diagnostic tests and management of minor complications.
2. Provide outpatient obstetrical care for essentially healthy women.
3. Provide individualized client teaching, counseling and anticipatory guidance for the current identified problem, weeks’ gestation, and social/cultural situation.
4. Perform accurate comprehensive health history, review of systems and physical examination, concluding with diagnosis and treatment.
5. Perform a comprehensive physical examination to identify the normal and abnormal changes associated with health and disease states.
6. Order, perform, and interpret diagnostic procedures and tests, as indicated by the history and physical examination, for pregnancy, acute and common primary care conditions.
7. Develop differential diagnoses based on clinical and laboratory data.
8. Differentiate and manage common primary care problems and other deviations from normal. Recognize emergencies and initiate emergency care/triage.
9. Manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. Initiate health promotion and disease prevention strategies that consider the individual’s age, developmental status, disability, culture, ethnicity, and sexual orientation to address their physical, psychosocial, and cultural needs.
10. Participate in the care of women with medical complications in collaboration with Obstetricians-Gynecologists and /or other physicians and health professionals as indicated and by sharing and receiving referrals for care with other professionals.
11. Complete necessary documentation appropriately, including coding and billing.
12. Instruct, supervise/precept and serve as mentor to students and trainees in medicine and nursing as assigned. Ensure a positive learning environment.
13. Contribute to site-specific quality improvement and data collection efforts.
14. Perform other duties as assigned.

As a patient-focused organization, the University of Utah Health Sciences exists to enhance the health and well-being of people through patient care, research and education. Success in this mission requires a culture of collaboration, excellence, leadership, and respect. The Health Sciences Center seeks faculty and staff who are committed to the values of compassion, collaboration, innovation, responsibility, diversity, integrity, quality and trust that are integral to our mission.
Responsibilities
1. Provide evidence-based care to women including ordering and evaluation of diagnostic tests and management of minor complications.
2. Provide outpatient obstetrical care for essentially healthy women.
3. Provide individualized client teaching, counseling and anticipatory guidance for the current identified problem, weeks’ gestation, and social/cultural situation.
4. Perform accurate comprehensive health history, review of systems and physical examination, concluding with diagnosis and treatment.
5. Perform a comprehensive physical examination to identify the normal and abnormal changes associated with health and disease states.
6. Order, perform, and interpret diagnostic procedures and tests, as indicated by the history and physical examination, for pregnancy, acute and common primary care conditions.
7. Develop differential diagnoses based on clinical and laboratory data.
8. Differentiate and manage common primary care problems and other deviations from normal. Recognize emergencies and initiate emergency care/triage.
9. Manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. Initiate health promotion and disease prevention strategies that consider the individual’s age, developmental status, disability, culture, ethnicity, and sexual orientation to address their physical, psychosocial, and cultural needs.
10. Participate in the care of women with medical complications in collaboration with Obstetricians-Gynecologists and /or other physicians and health professionals as indicated and by sharing and receiving referrals for care with other professionals.
11. Complete necessary documentation appropriately, including coding and billing.
12. Instruct, supervise/precept and serve as mentor to students and trainees in medicine and nursing as assigned. Ensure a positive learning environment.
13. Contribute to site-specific quality improvement and data collection efforts.
14. Perform other duties as assigned.

As a patient-focused organization, the University of Utah Health Sciences exists to enhance the health and well-being of people through patient care, research and education. Success in this mission requires a culture of collaboration, excellence, leadership, and respect. Responsibilities
1. Provide evidence-based care to women including ordering and evaluation of diagnostic tests and management of minor complications.
2. Provide outpatient obstetrical care for essentially healthy women.
3. Provide individualized client teaching, counseling and anticipatory guidance for the current identified problem, weeks’ gestation, and social/cultural situation.
4. Perform accurate comprehensive health history, review of systems and physical examination, concluding with diagnosis and treatment.
5. Perform a comprehensive physical examination to identify the normal and abnormal changes associated with health and disease states.
6. Order, perform, and interpret diagnostic procedures and tests, as indicated by the history and physical examination, for pregnancy, acute and common primary care conditions.
7. Develop differential diagnoses based on clinical and laboratory data.
8. Differentiate and manage common primary care problems and other deviations from normal. Recognize emergencies and initiate emergency care/triage.
9. Manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. Initiate health promotion and disease prevention strategies that consider the individual’s age, developmental status, disability, culture, ethnicity, and sexual orientation to address their physical, psychosocial, and cultural needs.
10. Participate in the care of women with medical complications in collaboration with Obstetricians-Gynecologists and /or other physicians and health professionals as indicated and by sharing and receiving referrals for care with other professionals.
11. Complete necessary documentation appropriately, including coding and billing.
12. Instruct, supervise/precept and serve as mentor to students and trainees in medicine and nursing as assigned. Ensure a positive learning environment.
13. Contribute to site-specific quality improvement and data collection efforts.
14. Perform other duties as assigned.

An OB-GYN, or Obstetrician-Gynecologist, diagnoses and treats various medical conditions that impact women’s health. The duties include diagnosing and monitoring illnesses and diseases, providing medical support to pregnant women, and performing routine check-ups on female patients.
ESSENTIAL DUTIES/RESPONSIBILITIES:
Diagnoses and treats conditions that affect women, such as certain types of cancer and conditions like menopause.
Works with expecting mothers to explain the childbirth process.
Performs routine checkups with patients.

The Women’s Health Nurse Practitioner (WHNP) hired into this position will manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. The position requires a considerable degree of independent skills and judgment necessary to monitor and respond to changes in patients’ condition.
As a patient-focused organization, the University of Utah Health Sciences exists to enhance the health and well-being of people through patient care, research and education. Success in this mission requires a culture of collaboration, excellence, leadership, and respect. The Health Sciences Center seeks faculty and staff who are committed to the values of compassion, collaboration, innovation, responsibility, diversity, integrity, quality and trust that are integral to our mission.
Responsibilities
1. Provide evidence-based care to women including ordering and evaluation of diagnostic tests and management of minor complications.
2. Provide outpatient obstetrical care for essentially healthy women.
3. Provide individualized client teaching, counseling and anticipatory guidance for the current identified problem, weeks’ gestation, and social/cultural situation.
4. Perform accurate comprehensive health history, review of systems and physical examination, concluding with diagnosis and treatment.
5. Perform a comprehensive physical examination to identify the normal and abnormal changes associated with health and disease states.
6. Order, perform, and interpret diagnostic procedures and tests, as indicated by the history and physical examination, for pregnancy, acute and common primary care conditions.
7. Develop differential diagnoses based on clinical and laboratory data.
8. Differentiate and manage common primary care problems and other deviations from normal. Recognize emergencies and initiate emergency care/triage.
9. Manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. Initiate health promotion and disease prevention strategies that consider the individual’s age, developmental status, disability, culture, ethnicity, and sexual orientation to address their physical, psychosocial, and cultural needs.
10. Participate in the care of women with medical complications in collaboration with Obstetricians-Gynecologists and /or other physicians and health professionals as indicated and by sharing and receiving referrals for care with other professionals.
11. Complete necessary documentation appropriately, including coding and billing.
12. Instruct, supervise/precept and serve as mentor to students and trainees in medicine and nursing as assigned. Ensure a positive learning environment.
13. Contribute to site-specific quality improvement and data collection efforts.
14. Perform other duties as assigned.
Minimum Qualifications

Perform counseling on birth control and placement of long-acting reversible contraception (LARCs) (i.e. IUDs, Nexplanon), possibly perform in office procedures like endometrial biopsy and colposcopy.

PRIMARY FUNCTIONS

1. Counsel and educate patients, conduct examinations, and take detailed medical histories.

2. Provide well-woman gynecological care, family planning advice, and prenatal care.

An OB-GYN, or Obstetrician-Gynecologist, diagnoses and treats various medical conditions that impact women’s health. The duties include diagnosing and monitoring illnesses and diseases, providing medical support to pregnant women, and performing routine check-ups on female patients.
ESSENTIAL DUTIES/RESPONSIBILITIES:
Diagnoses and treats conditions that affect women, such as certain types of cancer and conditions like menopause.
Works with expecting mothers to explain the childbirth process.
Performs routine checkups with patients.

The Women’s Health Nurse Practitioner (WHNP) hired into this position will manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. The position requires a considerable degree of independent skills and judgment necessary to monitor and respond to changes in patients’ condition.
As a patient-focused organization, the University of Utah Health Sciences exists to enhance the health and well-being of people through patient care, research and education. Success in this mission requires a culture of collaboration, excellence, leadership, and respect. The Health Sciences Center seeks faculty and staff who are committed to the values of compassion, collaboration, innovation, responsibility, diversity, integrity, quality and trust that are integral to our mission.
Responsibilities
1. Provide evidence-based care to women including ordering and evaluation of diagnostic tests and management of minor complications.
2. Provide outpatient obstetrical care for essentially healthy women.
3. Provide individualized client teaching, counseling and anticipatory guidance for the current identified problem, weeks’ gestation, and social/cultural situation.
4. Perform accurate comprehensive health history, review of systems and physical examination, concluding with diagnosis and treatment.
5. Perform a comprehensive physical examination to identify the normal and abnormal changes associated with health and disease states.
6. Order, perform, and interpret diagnostic procedures and tests, as indicated by the history and physical examination, for pregnancy, acute and common primary care conditions.
7. Develop differential diagnoses based on clinical and laboratory data.
8. Differentiate and manage common primary care problems and other deviations from normal. Recognize emergencies and initiate emergency care/triage.
9. Manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. Initiate health promotion and disease prevention strategies that consider the individual’s age, developmental status, disability, culture, ethnicity, and sexual orientation to address their physical, psychosocial, and cultural needs.
10. Participate in the care of women with medical complications in collaboration with Obstetricians-Gynecologists and /or other physicians and health professionals as indicated and by sharing and receiving referrals for care with other professionals.
11. Complete necessary documentation appropriately, including coding and billing.
12. Instruct, supervise/precept and serve as mentor to students and trainees in medicine and nursing as assigned. Ensure a positive learning environment.
13. Contribute to site-specific quality improvement and data collection efforts.
14. Perform other duties as assigned.

JOB SUMMARY

The Women’s Health NP position include but are not limited to providing advice, care, and support for women and their babies during pregnancy and the postnatal period. Perform diagnostic tests and procedures or refer tests as appropriate. Work closely with obstetricians and gynecologists in diagnosing and treating women with acute and chronic illnesses. Perform counseling on birth control and placement of long-acting reversible contraception (LARCs) (i.e. IUDs, Nexplanon), possibly perform in office procedures like endometrial biopsy and colposcopy.

PRIMARY FUNCTIONS

1. Counsel and educate patients, conduct examinations, and take detailed medical histories.

2. Provide well-woman gynecological care, family planning advice, and prenatal care.

The Women’s Health Nurse Practitioner (WHNP) hired into this position will manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. The position requires a considerable degree of independent skills and judgment necessary to monitor and respond to changes in patients’ condition.
As a patient-focused organization, the University of Utah Health Sciences exists to enhance the health and well-being of people through patient care, research and education. Success in this mission requires a culture of collaboration, excellence, leadership, and respect. The Health Sciences Center seeks faculty and staff who are committed to the values of compassion, collaboration, innovation, responsibility, diversity, integrity, quality and trust that are integral to our mission.
Responsibilities
1. Provide evidence-based care to women including ordering and evaluation of diagnostic tests and management of minor complications.
2. Provide outpatient obstetrical care for essentially healthy women.
3. Provide individualized client teaching, counseling and anticipatory guidance for the current identified problem, weeks’ gestation, and social/cultural situation.
4. Perform accurate comprehensive health history, review of systems and physical examination, concluding with diagnosis and treatment.
5. Perform a comprehensive physical examination to identify the normal and abnormal changes associated with health and disease states.
6. Order, perform, and interpret diagnostic procedures and tests, as indicated by the history and physical examination, for pregnancy, acute and common primary care conditions.
7. Develop differential diagnoses based on clinical and laboratory data.
8. Differentiate and manage common primary care problems and other deviations from normal. Recognize emergencies and initiate emergency care/triage.
9. Manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. Initiate health promotion and disease prevention strategies that consider the individual’s age, developmental status, disability, culture, ethnicity, and sexual orientation to address their physical, psychosocial, and cultural needs.
10. Participate in the care of women with medical complications in collaboration with Obstetricians-Gynecologists and /or other physicians and health professionals as indicated and by sharing and receiving referrals for care with other professionals.
11. Complete necessary documentation appropriately, including coding and billing.
12. Instruct, supervise/precept and serve as mentor to students and trainees in medicine and nursing as assigned. Ensure a positive learning environment.
13. Contribute to site-specific quality improvement and data collection efforts.
14. Perform other duties as assigned.

As a patient-focused organization, the University of Utah Health Sciences exists to enhance the health and well-being of people through patient care, research and education. Success in this mission requires a culture of collaboration, excellence, leadership, and respect. The Health Sciences Center seeks faculty and staff who are committed to the values of compassion, collaboration, innovation, responsibility, diversity, integrity, quality and trust that are integral to our mission.
Responsibilities
1. Provide evidence-based care to women including ordering and evaluation of diagnostic tests and management of minor complications.
2. Provide outpatient obstetrical care for essentially healthy women.
3. Provide individualized client teaching, counseling and anticipatory guidance for the current identified problem, weeks’ gestation, and social/cultural situation.
4. Perform accurate comprehensive health history, review of systems and physical examination, concluding with diagnosis and treatment.
5. Perform a comprehensive physical examination to identify the normal and abnormal changes associated with health and disease states.
6. Order, perform, and interpret diagnostic procedures and tests, as indicated by the history and physical examination, for pregnancy, acute and common primary care conditions.
7. Develop differential diagnoses based on clinical and laboratory data.
8. Differentiate and manage common primary care problems and other deviations from normal. Recognize emergencies and initiate emergency care/triage.
9. Manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. Initiate health promotion and disease prevention strategies that consider the individual’s age, developmental status, disability, culture, ethnicity, and sexual orientation to address their physical, psychosocial, and cultural needs.
10. Participate in the care of women with medical complications in collaboration with Obstetricians-Gynecologists and /or other physicians and health professionals as indicated and by sharing and receiving referrals for care with other professionals.
11. Complete necessary documentation appropriately, including coding and billing.
12. Instruct, supervise/precept and serve as mentor to students and trainees in medicine and nursing as assigned. Ensure a positive learning environment.
13. Contribute to site-specific quality improvement and data collection efforts.
14. Perform other duties as assigned.

The Women’s Health Nurse Practitioner (WHNP) hired into this position will manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. The position requires a considerable degree of independent skills and judgment necessary to monitor and respond to changes in patients’ condition.
As a patient-focused organization, the University of Utah Health Sciences exists to enhance the health and well-being of people through patient care, research and education. Success in this mission requires a culture of collaboration, excellence, leadership, and respect. The Health Sciences Center seeks faculty and staff who are committed to the values of compassion, collaboration, innovation, responsibility, diversity, integrity, quality and trust that are integral to our mission.
Responsibilities
1. Provide evidence-based care to women including ordering and evaluation of diagnostic tests and management of minor complications.
2. Provide outpatient obstetrical care for essentially healthy women.
3. Provide individualized client teaching, counseling and anticipatory guidance for the current identified problem, weeks’ gestation, and social/cultural situation.
4. Perform accurate comprehensive health history, review of systems and physical examination, concluding with diagnosis and treatment.
5. Perform a comprehensive physical examination to identify the normal and abnormal changes associated with health and disease states.
6. Order, perform, and interpret diagnostic procedures and tests, as indicated by the history and physical examination, for pregnancy, acute and common primary care conditions.
7. Develop differential diagnoses based on clinical and laboratory data.
8. Differentiate and manage common primary care problems and other deviations from normal. Recognize emergencies and initiate emergency care/triage.
9. Manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. Initiate health promotion and disease prevention strategies that consider the individual’s age, developmental status, disability, culture, ethnicity, and sexual orientation to address their physical, psychosocial, and cultural needs.
10. Participate in the care of women with medical complications in collaboration with Obstetricians-Gynecologists and /or other physicians and health professionals as indicated and by sharing and receiving referrals for care with other professionals.
11. Complete necessary documentation appropriately, including coding and billing.
12. Instruct, supervise/precept and serve as mentor to students and trainees in medicine and nursing as assigned. Ensure a positive learning environment.
13. Contribute to site-specific quality improvement and data collection efforts.
14. Perform other duties as assigned.

The Women’s Health Nurse Practitioner (WHNP) hired into this position will manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. The position requires a considerable degree of independent skills and judgment necessary to monitor and respond to changes in patients’ condition.
As a patient-focused organization, the University of Utah Health Sciences exists to enhance the health and well-being of people through patient care, research and education. Success in this mission requires a culture of collaboration, excellence, leadership, and respect. The Health Sciences Center seeks faculty and staff who are committed to the values of compassion, collaboration, innovation, responsibility, diversity, integrity, quality and trust that are integral to our mission.
Responsibilities
1. Provide evidence-based care to women including ordering and evaluation of diagnostic tests and management of minor complications.
2. Provide outpatient obstetrical care for essentially healthy women.
3. Provide individualized client teaching, counseling and anticipatory guidance for the current identified problem, weeks’ gestation, and social/cultural situation.
4. Perform accurate comprehensive health history, review of systems and physical examination, concluding with diagnosis and treatment.
5. Perform a comprehensive physical examination to identify the normal and abnormal changes associated with health and disease states.
6. Order, perform, and interpret diagnostic procedures and tests, as indicated by the history and physical examination, for pregnancy, acute and common primary care conditions.
7. Develop differential diagnoses based on clinical and laboratory data.
8. Differentiate and manage common primary care problems and other deviations from normal. Recognize emergencies and initiate emergency care/triage.
9. Manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. Initiate health promotion and disease prevention strategies that consider the individual’s age, developmental status, disability, culture, ethnicity, and sexual orientation to address their physical, psychosocial, and cultural needs.
10. Participate in the care of women with medical complications in collaboration with Obstetricians-Gynecologists and /or other physicians and health professionals as indicated and by sharing and receiving referrals for care with other professionals.
11. Complete necessary documentation appropriately, including coding and billing.
12. Instruct, supervise/precept and serve as mentor to students and trainees in medicine and nursing as assigned. Ensure a positive learning environment.
13. Contribute to site-specific quality improvement and data collection efforts.
14. Perform other duties as assigned.

The Women’s Health Nurse Practitioner (WHNP) hired into this position will manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. The position requires a considerable degree of independent skills and judgment necessary to monitor and respond to changes in patients’ condition.
As a patient-focused organization, the University of Utah Health Sciences exists to enhance the health and well-being of people through patient care, research and education. Success in this mission requires a culture of collaboration, excellence, leadership, and respect. The Health Sciences Center seeks faculty and staff who are committed to the values of compassion, collaboration, innovation, responsibility, diversity, integrity, quality and trust that are integral to our mission.
Responsibilities
1. Provide evidence-based care to women including ordering and evaluation of diagnostic tests and management of minor complications.
2. Provide outpatient obstetrical care for essentially healthy women.
3. Provide individualized client teaching, counseling and anticipatory guidance for the current identified problem, weeks’ gestation, and social/cultural situation.
4. Perform accurate comprehensive health history, review of systems and physical examination, concluding with diagnosis and treatment.
5. Perform a comprehensive physical examination to identify the normal and abnormal changes associated with health and disease states.
6. Order, perform, and interpret diagnostic procedures and tests, as indicated by the history and physical examination, for pregnancy, acute and common primary care conditions.
7. Develop differential diagnoses based on clinical and laboratory data.
8. Differentiate and manage common primary care problems and other deviations from normal. Recognize emergencies and initiate emergency care/triage.
9. Manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. Initiate health promotion and disease prevention strategies that consider the individual’s age, developmental status, disability, culture, ethnicity, and sexual orientation to address their physical, psychosocial, and cultural needs.
10. Participate in the care of women with medical complications in collaboration with Obstetricians-Gynecologists and /or other physicians and health professionals as indicated and by sharing and receiving referrals for care with other professionals.
11. Complete necessary documentation appropriately, including coding and billing.
12. Instruct, supervise/precept and serve as mentor to students and trainees in medicine and nursing as assigned. Ensure a positive learning environment.
13. Contribute to site-specific quality improvement and data collection efforts.
14. Perform other duties as assigned.

The Women’s Health Nurse Practitioner (WHNP) hired into this position will manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. The position requires a considerable degree of independent skills and judgment necessary to monitor and respond to changes in patients’ condition.
As a patient-focused organization, the University of Utah Health Sciences exists to enhance the health and well-being of people through patient care, research and education. Success in this mission requires a culture of collaboration, excellence, leadership, and respect. The Health Sciences Center seeks faculty and staff who are committed to the values of compassion, collaboration, innovation, responsibility, diversity, integrity, quality and trust that are integral to our mission.
Responsibilities
1. Provide evidence-based care to women including ordering and evaluation of diagnostic tests and management of minor complications.
2. Provide outpatient obstetrical care for essentially healthy women.
3. Provide individualized client teaching, counseling and anticipatory guidance for the current identified problem, weeks’ gestation, and social/cultural situation.
4. Perform accurate comprehensive health history, review of systems and physical examination, concluding with diagnosis and treatment.
5. Perform a comprehensive physical examination to identify the normal and abnormal changes associated with health and disease states.
6. Order, perform, and interpret diagnostic procedures and tests, as indicated by the history and physical examination, for pregnancy, acute and common primary care conditions.
7. Develop differential diagnoses based on clinical and laboratory data.
8. Differentiate and manage common primary care problems and other deviations from normal. Recognize emergencies and initiate emergency care/triage.
9. Manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. Initiate health promotion and disease prevention strategies that consider the individual’s age, developmental status, disability, culture, ethnicity, and sexual orientation to address their physical, psychosocial, and cultural needs.
10. Participate in the care of women with medical complications in collaboration with Obstetricians-Gynecologists and /or other physicians and health professionals as indicated and by sharing and receiving referrals for care with other professionals.
11. Complete necessary documentation appropriately, including coding and billing.
12. Instruct, supervise/precept and serve as mentor to students and trainees in medicine and nursing as assigned. Ensure a positive learning environment.
13. Contribute to site-specific quality improvement and data collection efforts.
14. Perform other duties as assigned.

An OB-GYN, or Obstetrician-Gynecologist, diagnoses and treats various medical conditions that impact women’s health. The duties include diagnosing and monitoring illnesses and diseases, providing medical support to pregnant women, and performing routine check-ups on female patients.

The Women’s Health Nurse Practitioner (WHNP) hired into this position will manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. The position requires a considerable degree of independent skills and judgment necessary to monitor and respond to changes in patients’ condition.
As a patient-focused organization, the University of Utah Health Sciences exists to enhance the health and well-being of people through patient care, research and education. Success in this mission requires a culture of collaboration, excellence, leadership, and respect. The Health Sciences Center seeks faculty and staff who are committed to the values of compassion, collaboration, innovation, responsibility, diversity, integrity, quality and trust that are integral to our mission.
Responsibilities
1. Provide evidence-based care to women including ordering and evaluation of diagnostic tests and management of minor complications.
2. Provide outpatient obstetrical care for essentially healthy women.
3. Provide individualized client teaching, counseling and anticipatory guidance for the current identified problem, weeks’ gestation, and social/cultural situation.
4. Perform accurate comprehensive health history, review of systems and physical examination, concluding with diagnosis and treatment.
5. Perform a comprehensive physical examination to identify the normal and abnormal changes associated with health and disease states.
6. Order, perform, and interpret diagnostic procedures and tests, as indicated by the history and physical examination, for pregnancy, acute and common primary care conditions.
7. Develop differential diagnoses based on clinical and laboratory data.
8. Differentiate and manage common primary care problems and other deviations from normal. Recognize emergencies and initiate emergency care/triage.
9. Manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. Initiate health promotion and disease prevention strategies that consider the individual’s age, developmental status, disability, culture, ethnicity, and sexual orientation to address their physical, psychosocial, and cultural needs.
10. Participate in the care of women with medical complications in collaboration with Obstetricians-Gynecologists and /or other physicians and health professionals as indicated and by sharing and receiving referrals for care with other professionals.
11. Complete necessary documentation appropriately, including coding and billing.
12. Instruct, supervise/precept and serve as mentor to students and trainees in medicine and nursing as assigned. Ensure a positive learning environment.
13. Contribute to site-specific quality improvement and data collection efforts.
14. Perform other duties as assigned.

The Women’s Health Nurse Practitioner (WHNP) hired into this position will manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. The position requires a considerable degree of independent skills and judgment necessary to monitor and respond to changes in patients’ condition.
As a patient-focused organization, the University of Utah Health Sciences exists to enhance the health and well-being of people through patient care, research and education. Success in this mission requires a culture of collaboration, excellence, leadership, and respect. The Health Sciences Center seeks faculty and staff who are committed to the values of compassion, collaboration, innovation, responsibility, diversity, integrity, quality and trust that are integral to our mission.
Responsibilities
1. Provide evidence-based care to women including ordering and evaluation of diagnostic tests and management of minor complications.
2. Provide outpatient obstetrical care for essentially healthy women.
3. Provide individualized client teaching, counseling and anticipatory guidance for the current identified problem, weeks’ gestation, and social/cultural situation.
4. Perform accurate comprehensive health history, review of systems and physical examination, concluding with diagnosis and treatment.
5. Perform a comprehensive physical examination to identify the normal and abnormal changes associated with health and disease states.
6. Order, perform, and interpret diagnostic procedures and tests, as indicated by the history and physical examination, for pregnancy, acute and common primary care conditions.
7. Develop differential diagnoses based on clinical and laboratory data.
8. Differentiate and manage common primary care problems and other deviations from normal. Recognize emergencies and initiate emergency care/triage.
9. Manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. Initiate health promotion and disease prevention strategies that consider the individual’s age, developmental status, disability, culture, ethnicity, and sexual orientation to address their physical, psychosocial, and cultural needs.
10. Participate in the care of women with medical complications in collaboration with Obstetricians-Gynecologists and /or other physicians and health professionals as indicated and by sharing and receiving referrals for care with other professionals.
11. Complete necessary documentation appropriately, including coding and billing.
12. Instruct, supervise/precept and serve as mentor to students and trainees in medicine and nursing as assigned. Ensure a positive learning environment.
13. Contribute to site-specific quality improvement and data collection efforts.
14. Perform other duties as assigned.

As a patient-focused organization, the University of Utah Health Sciences exists to enhance the health and well-being of people through patient care, research and education. Success in this mission requires a culture of collaboration, excellence, leadership, and respect. The Health Sciences Center seeks faculty and staff who are committed to the values of compassion, collaboration, innovation, responsibility, diversity, integrity, quality and trust that are integral to our mission.
Responsibilities
1. Provide evidence-based care to women including ordering and evaluation of diagnostic tests and management of minor complications.
2. Provide outpatient obstetrical care for essentially healthy women.
3. Provide individualized client teaching, counseling and anticipatory guidance for the current identified problem, weeks’ gestation, and social/cultural situation.
4. Perform accurate comprehensive health history, review of systems and physical examination, concluding with diagnosis and treatment.
5. Perform a comprehensive physical examination to identify the normal and abnormal changes associated with health and disease states.
6. Order, perform, and interpret diagnostic procedures and tests, as indicated by the history and physical examination, for pregnancy, acute and common primary care conditions.
7. Develop differential diagnoses based on clinical and laboratory data.
8. Differentiate and manage common primary care problems and other deviations from normal. Recognize emergencies and initiate emergency care/triage.
9. Manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. Initiate health promotion and disease prevention strategies that consider the individual’s age, developmental status, disability, culture, ethnicity, and sexual orientation to address their physical, psychosocial, and cultural needs.
10. Participate in the care of women with medical complications in collaboration with Obstetricians-Gynecologists and /or other physicians and health professionals as indicated and by sharing and receiving referrals for care with other professionals.
11. Complete necessary documentation appropriately, including coding and billing.
12. Instruct, supervise/precept and serve as mentor to students and trainees in medicine and nursing as assigned. Ensure a positive learning environment.
13. Contribute to site-specific quality improvement and data collection efforts.
14. Perform other duties as assigned.

The Health Sciences Center seeks faculty and staff who are committed to the values of compassion, collaboration, innovation, responsibility, diversity, integrity, quality and trust that are integral to our mission.
Responsibilities
1. Provide evidence-based care to women including ordering and evaluation of diagnostic tests and management of minor complications.
2. Provide outpatient obstetrical care for essentially healthy women.
3. Provide individualized client teaching, counseling and anticipatory guidance for the current identified problem, weeks’ gestation, and social/cultural situation.
4. Perform accurate comprehensive health history, review of systems and physical examination, concluding with diagnosis and treatment.
5. Perform a comprehensive physical examination to identify the normal and abnormal changes associated with health and disease states.
6. Order, perform, and interpret diagnostic procedures and tests, as indicated by the history and physical examination, for pregnancy, acute and common primary care conditions.
7. Develop differential diagnoses based on clinical and laboratory data.
8. Differentiate and manage common primary care problems and other deviations from normal. Recognize emergencies and initiate emergency care/triage.
9. Manage the general health needs of women throughout the life cycle. Initiate health promotion and disease prevention strategies that consider the individual’s age, developmental status, disability, culture, ethnicity, and sexual orientation to address their physical, psychosocial, and cultural needs.
10. Participate in the care of women with medical complications in collaboration with Obstetricians-Gynecologists and /or other physicians and health professionals as indicated and by sharing and receiving referrals for care with other professionals.
11. Complete necessary documentation appropriately, including coding and billing.
12. Instruct, supervise/precept and serve as mentor to students and trainees in medicine and nursing as assigned. Ensure a positive learning environment.
13. Contribute to site-specific quality improvement and data collection efforts.
14. Perform other duties as assigned.
